name: Ragnar Trail North Shore Oahu - HI
intro:
The legendary North Shore of Oahu is home to beautiful beaches, monumental surfing, and now, a Ragnar Trail Relay! Happening on April 21-22, at Turtle Bay Resort, Ragnar Trail North Shore Oahu-HI presented by Salomon is a chance to experience the magic of a Ragnar Trail Relay in an exotic place that features the most awe-inspiring wonders Mother Nature has to offer.

Located on a peninsula between two stunning bays, white sand beaches, palm trees, green lawns, ocean breeze and pristine single track trails await you and your team of 8 members (or ultra-team of 4 members). You and your team will conquer a series of three trails or “loops” that start and stop at Ragnar Village, from Friday, into the night, and ending on Saturday. The trails at Turtle Bay twist, swoop, and climb through a lush jungle and along white sand beaches.

When you’re not running, you’ll experience the party-vibe at Ragnar Village complete with s’mores, hammocks, plush grass, palm trees and magical views. Camp out with your team, or check into a 5-star resort that is walking distance to the trails and Ragnar Village. Mark your running calendar for April 21-22, and feel the warm embrace of the Aloha spirit.

KAMA'AINA? Check here for special pricing! *offical state of Hawaii driver's license required.
training:
Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

  • How to Run on Snowy or Icy Trails
  • How to Run in Mud

charity:
Turtle Bay Foundation

 

The Turtle Bay Foundation was established in 2012 to enrich Oahu’s North Shore through environmental, educational and cultural opportunities. The Foundation oversees the numerous contributions of Turtle Bay Resort to Oahu charities, acting as a partner in the community and supporting the resort’s mission of making one of the world’s last great places even better.

meta_description: The legendary North Shore of Oahu is home to beautiful beaches, monumental surfing, and now, a Ragnar Trail Relay! Happening on April 21-22, at Turtle Bay Resort, Ragnar Trail North Shore Oahu-HI presented by Salomon is a chance to experience the magic of a Ragnar Trail Relay in an exotic place that features the most awe-inspiring wonders Mother Nature has to offer.

legs.name: Green Loop - Magic Bus Trail
legs.description: Jump on the magic bus for a joy ride through jungle. The Green Loop leaves the idyllic setting of Ragnar Village and sets out with the Yellow Loop on a mellow double-track for a half mile warm up. A sharp right turn onto single-track splits you away from Yellow and takes you on a swooping ride through the dense North Shore jungle. Rumor has it that during the construction of this trail, an old beat up bus was uncovered from the jungle. Surprised by their find, the trail builders created trail features and berms alongside the bus and aptly named the trail for their find. After 2 miles of fun single-track this loop joins back with Yellow to run through an old Banyan tree (yes, you read that right, quite amazing) and then pop-out of the trees to run alongside the insanely beautiful backdrop of Kawela (Turtle) Bay. Slap yourself and keep running, you are almost done with the Green Loop, and yes, it was magical.

legs.name: Yellow Loop - Kuilima Trail
legs.description: With over a mile of newly cut single-track trail, the Kuilima Trail has been especially designed and built for Ragnar Trail North Shore runners.  You are gonna love the twisty turny laps  through the dense jungle landscape that defines Kuilima Bay.  Long stretches of fast straight away will give you time to catch your breath before you head back in to jam it out on the ups, downs, twists and turns before hitting the beach and shooting past Turtle Bay Resort back to Ragnar Village.

legs.name: Red Loop - Kahuku Point Trail
legs.description: Wow. Just Wow. Due to the extreme beauty, you may not notice how hard it is to run through sand. Or maybe you will, but that is why it is the Red Loop. The first ¾ of a mile take you past Turtle Bay Resort proper. Have a glimpse of the beach loungers where you may be parked after the race but for now, we run! Around mile 1 the trail floats down a corridor of trees overlooking the beach. The footing is fairly solid and the views are very solid. But the next mile are tough, as you tread through the sand , but the views are your payback. Around 1.5 miles you climb the sand dunes of Kahuku Point and make a U-turn to continue along the dunes. If you catch this run at sunset, or at sunrise, or during the moon, or any other time, you will be blown away by the beauty…and probably the wind. Just after mile 2 a right turn pulls you away from the ocean and puts your feet back on solid ground. From here back to the village is a flat and fast double-track through the trees. Turn on the afterburners and scroll through the memories of the view of Kahuku Point.

Adventure
